[
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think we need impredicativity <em>or</em> a NNO to define what a finite sobject is. Couldn't we say that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is finite iff it has decidable equality,<br>\n(i) there exists a (necessarily unique) least map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f:(X \\to 2) \\to 2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span> (under the pointwise ordering) satisfying the property that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>λ</mi><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(\\lambda x. 0) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">λ</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> and for any <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span></span></span></span> with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(m) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, we have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>∨</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(m \\lor (=a)) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> and<br>\n(ii) this <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> also satisfies <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>λ</mi><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(\\lambda x.1) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">λ</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 197165734,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589212416
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This says the same as the impredicative finitary definition given on the nlab (give or take), but doesn't need power set (as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> has decidable equality), and has the existence of 'the collection of finite subobjects' as a requirement as part of the definition, as opposed to something which we know exists already.</p>",
        "id": 197165737,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589212419
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not sure how this could be extended to subfiniteness or k-finiteness, though.</p>",
        "id": 197165892,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589212482
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what exactly does f do here?</p>",
        "id": 197166233,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1589212619
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Characterises the finite decidable subsets - for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span></span></span></span> the characteristic map of a decidable subset, we should have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(m)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> iff <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span></span></span></span> is a finite subset.</p>",
        "id": 197166464,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589212687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>hmm...</p>",
        "id": 197166599,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1589212742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It seems like you would get K-finiteness just by dropping the hypothesis of decidable equality, right?</p>",
        "id": 197166715,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589212786
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>well, you have no way of stating this w/o either impredicativity or deceq</p>",
        "id": 197166925,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1589212867
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, because you can't gaurantee that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>m</mi><mo>∨</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">m \\lor (=a)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.55556em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is then a decidable subset.</p>",
        "id": 197166937,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589212872
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Why do you need to use <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 197166965,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589212891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>because having a subobject classifier is impredicative</p>",
        "id": 197166985,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1589212901
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(so this is not directly relevant to topoi, of course—but maybe to finiteness in other kinds of categories)</p>",
        "id": 197167123,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1589212946
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, I don't know about these silly things <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
        "id": 197167140,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1589212951
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"294701\">@Jem</span> hmm, i think</p>\n<ol>\n<li>youd want <em>least</em> rather than minimal</li>\n<li>youd want it to be least satisfying condition (i), and then condition (ii) holds of it to make the whole object finite</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 197167479,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1589213082
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, that's what I meant to mean. &gt;.&lt;</p>",
        "id": 197167632,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589213143
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you can define B-finite, then you can define the others in terms of B-finite sets, can't you? K-finite is 'admits a surjection from a B-finite set'.</p>",
        "id": 197177553,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Doel",
        "timestamp": 1589217702
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, that works if you have quantification over types or an enumeration of B-finite sets.</p>",
        "id": 197177715,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589217762
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think we have either of those in the internal logic of an arbitrary topos (or LCCC) though, do we?</p>",
        "id": 197177750,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589217787
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Huh? Why do you need those?</p>",
        "id": 197177762,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1589217793
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well presumably you'd formalise \"admits a surjection from a B-finite set\" as \"there exists a B-finite set and a surjection from that B-finite set\", and in order to state that you'd need one of those.</p>",
        "id": 197177909,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589217885
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You'd need it to internalize the notion of (e.g.) K-finite, but not to exhibit that any particular thing is K-finite.</p>",
        "id": 197177910,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Doel",
        "timestamp": 1589217886
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah.</p>",
        "id": 197177934,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589217899
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"294701\">@Jem</span>   But if I take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> to be a non-trivial subobject of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, wouldn't that be finite according to your definition ?</p>",
        "id": 197179536,
        "sender_full_name": "zigzag",
        "timestamp": 1589218670
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't see why it would be (as we would need it to be inhabited to actually adjoin an element) but also don't see why it wouldn't be (the idea I had sketched fell through on closer inspection). What did you have in mind?</p>",
        "id": 197185708,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589221779
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The definition can be amended by adding \"any decidable subset of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is empty or inhabited\" to exclude cases like that.</p>",
        "id": 197185733,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589221797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So hopefully that would fix it.</p>",
        "id": 197185785,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589221805
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not to be dismissive, but I'm happy to work impredicatively/with power objects if it simplifies things enough to get to an answer to what I was asking about <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 197185942,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1589221913
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Split the topic off so both can be talked about without interfering with each other</p>",
        "id": 197190513,
        "sender_full_name": "Jem",
        "timestamp": 1589224115
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>mmm roughly, if you reason internally to some weak set theory, suppose that you have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mo>∗</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\subseteq \\{*\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">∗</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> and you want to show it is finite using <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi><mi>p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda p. 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">λ</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> as witness (it trivally satisfies the closure property of i) and ii)). So you want to show that any <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∅</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(\\emptyset) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">∅</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> and with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>∪</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>a</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(p) = 1 \\Rightarrow f(p \\cup \\{a\\}) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∪</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> is in fact constanty <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>. </p>\n<p>To this end, assume you are given some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p : A \\to 2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span>. If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(p) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> we are fine, otherwise <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(p) = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>. In that case, I would claim that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> is empty, because, if you suppose that you are given the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∗</mo><mo>∈</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">* \\in A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> you can show that you have only two <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p : A \\to 2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span> with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(p) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> because of the closure properties. But if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span></span></span></span> was empty, then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>λ</mi><mi>x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p = \\lambda x. 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">λ</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> and, by your first closure property, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(p) = 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">p</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span>, which is a contradiction.</p>\n<p>I don't know about the fix, but I would remain very cautious until I see a proof that it coincides with the usual notion. Finiteness is a tricky topic :)</p>",
        "id": 197199640,
        "sender_full_name": "zigzag",
        "timestamp": 1589228493
    },
